<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">A CRIMINAL DEFENSE MERGER <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Criminal defense work, once shunned by most of New Yorkâs top law firms, is looking increasingly lucrative. One of the lawyers specializing in representing the accused, Charles A. Stillman, is announcing on Monday that his firm, Stillman &#038; Friedman, has combined with Ballard Spahr, an old-line Philadelphia firm looking to enter the New York market and expand its criminal defense practice, <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/06/30/stillman-friedman-merger-with-ballard-spahr-shows-growing-status-of-corporate-criminal-defense/">DealBookâs Peter Lattman reports</a>. Ballardâs New York office will be called Ballard Spahr Stillman &#038; Friedman.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe combination speaks to a shift that has taken place over decades, of corporate firms making a core business line out of white-collar work, including conducting internal investigations, handling foreign-bribery cases and representing executives in a number of scandals. As firms struggle to increase revenue, they realize that <b>representing business people behaving badly is good for the bottom line</b>,â Mr. Lattman writes. Mark S. Stewart, chairman of Ballard Spahr, said Stillman &#038; Friedman was âa perfect fit.â</p>
